<NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">One</NUMEX> common way of measuring inventory is to calculate the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">I/S</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">ratio‚</ENAMEX>Äîthat is, the ratio of total finished good inventories to total sales. This measure allows <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">one</NUMEX> to compare inventories in <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">firms</ENAMEX> with different sales volumes. We calculated the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">I/S</ENAMEX> ratio for <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">suppliers</ENAMEX> in our matched sample and then compared those with the ratios of <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">suppliers</ENAMEX> that used different combinations of the <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">four</NUMEX> manufacturing practices. Figure <NUMEX TYPE="CARDINAL">14.2</NUMEX> illustrates the impact of manufacturing practices on average inventory levels.
